   {:e #blake3 "3f1967fadf383693c9321903acae1debc2f6aba1fd2c672ebaac7d616627280a" :a :task/description :v "BACKGROUND: The calibration loop (OBSERVER-4) learns boundary WEIGHTS. Boundary discovery (OBSERVER-5) learns new RELATIONSHIPS between known categories. But neither learns the ONTOLOGY — what categories of knowledge exist. When observations cluster in attribute space but dont match any declared claim type, thats an emergent category the policy missed. This closes the final loop: the system learns not just what coherence means, but what KINDS of knowledge exist in this domain.. APPROACH: (1) fn discover_categories(store, policy: PolicyConfig) -> Vec<ProposedCategory>. (2) Cluster observations by attribute similarity: confidence range, downstream effects (did this lead to task creation? spec creation? witness?), keyword patterns, entity-type of related entities. (3) For each cluster that does NOT match a declared claim-type or evidence-type pattern: compute cluster coherence score (how tight is the cluster?) and frequency (how often does this pattern recur?). (4) If coherence > 0.7 AND frequency > 10 occurrences: propose as new category. (5) ProposedCategory includes: suggested name (from most common keywords), attribute pattern, example observations (3-5 representative datoms), suggested boundary (which existing category should this align with?). (6) braid discover --categories shows proposed categories for user review. (7) braid discover --accept-category <id> transacts new claim-type or evidence-type policy datoms.. ACCEPTANCE: (A) On our 48K-datom store: at least 1 emergent category detected (likely: implementation-insight, methodology-reflection, or architecture-observation). (B) Proposed categories do not duplicate declared ones. (C) Cluster coherence score is in [0,1]. (D) braid discover --accept-category produces valid policy datoms. (E) After accepting a new category, F(S) components reflect the expanded ontology. DEPENDS-ON: OBSERVER-5 (t-eafab6d9), POLICY-CONFIG (t-708bd7e9). FILE: crates/braid-kernel/src/discover.rs" :op :assert}
